  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- The USA PATRIOT Act\n- The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity)\n\n3. Key Regulatory Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n\n4. Penalties:\n- Significant fines\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset forfeiture\n\nThese statutes make it illegal to conduct financial transactions designed to conceal the origins of illegally obtained money, and they require financial institutions to report suspicious activities.\n\nState-level statutes also exist that complement federal money laundering laws, providing additional legal frameworks to combat financial crimes.",
